content:
Last week I had a chance to attend a truly great 2-day tutorial by Philip Schultz and Wilker Aziz. It was held in Mathematikon, Heidelberg and guys really did an amazing job. You can find the slides and a practice notebook on the tutorial’s official github page.
This was my first touch with variatoinal inference and DGMs, so my head was spinning from the start. I tried to keep up as long as I can, finally losing a grip on the second day. Nevertheless, I managed to gather my thoughts over the weekend, by going through my notes and finishing the coding part of the tutorial. You can find the solved jupyter notebook at my github. This post is an attempt to describe what I learned on a very high level, and in the process, wrap my head around it.
To be continued&hellip;
